# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gene-therapy-vectors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The first attempt at modifying human DNA was performed in 1980, by Martin Cline, but the first successful nuclear gene transfer in humans, approved by the National Institutes of Health, was performed in May 1989.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The first therapeutic use of gene transfer as well as the first direct insertion of human DNA into the nuclear genome was performed by French Anderson in a trial starting in September 1990.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Between 1989 and December 2018, over 2,900 clinical trials were conducted, with more than half of them in phase I.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In 2003, Gendicine became the first gene therapy to receive regulatory approval.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Most of gene therapy approaches have utilized adeno-associated viruses (AAVs) and lentiviruses for performing gene insertions, *in vivo* and *ex vivo*, respectively.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] AAVs are characterized by stabilizing the viral capsid, lower immunogenicity, ability to transduce both dividing and nondividing cells, the potential to integrate site specifically and to achieve long-term expression in the in-vivo treatment.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] ASO / siRNA approaches such as those conducted by Alnylam and Ionis Pharmaceuticals require non-viral delivery systems, and utilize alternative mechanisms for trafficking to liver cells by way of GalNAc transporters.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Not all medical procedures that introduce alterations to a patient's genetic makeup can be considered gene therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Bone marrow transplantation and organ transplants in general have been found to introduce foreign DNA into patients.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Gene therapy was first conceptualized in the 1960s, when the feasibility of adding new genetic functions to mammalian cells began to be researched.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Several methods to do so were tested, including injecting genes with a micropipette directly into a living mammalian cell, and exposing cells to a precipitate of DNA that contained the desired genes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Scientists theorized that a virus could also be used as a vehicle, or vector, to deliver new genes into cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] One of the first scientists to report the successful direct incorporation of functional DNA into a mammalian cell was biochemist Dr.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Lorraine Marquardt Kraus (6 September 1922 – 1 July 2016) at the University of Tennessee Health Science Center in Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In 1961, she managed to genetically alter the hemoglobin of cells from bone marrow taken from a patient with sickle cell anaemia.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] She did this by incubating the patient's cells in tissue culture with DNA extracted from a donor with normal hemoglobin.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The first attempt, an unsuccessful one, at gene therapy (as well as the first case of medical transfer of foreign genes into humans not counting organ transplantation) was performed by geneticist Martin Cline of the University of California, Los Angeles in California, United States on 10 July 1980.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Cline claimed that one of the genes in his patients was active six months later, though he never published this data or had it verified.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] After extensive research on animals throughout the 1980s and a 1989 bacterial gene tagging trial on humans, the first gene therapy widely accepted as a success was demonstrated in a trial that started on 14 September 1990, when Ashanthi DeSilva was treated for ADA-SCID.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The first somatic treatment that produced a permanent genetic change was initiated in 1993.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The goal was to cure malignant brain tumors by using recombinant DNA to transfer a gene making the tumor cells sensitive to a drug that in turn would cause the tumor cells to die.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The polymers are either translated into proteins, interfere with target gene expression, or possibly correct genetic mutations.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The most common form uses DNA that encodes a functional, therapeutic gene to replace a mutated gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The polymer molecule is packaged within a "vector", which carries the molecule inside cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Early clinical failures led to dismissals of gene therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Clinical successes since 2006 regained researchers' attention, although as of 2014, it was still largely an experimental technique.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] These include treatment of retinal diseases Leber's congenital amaurosis and choroideremia, X-linked SCID, ADA-SCID, adrenoleukodystrophy, chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL), acute lymphocytic leukemia (ALL), multiple myeloma, haemophilia, and Parkinson's disease.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Between 2013 and April 2014, US companies invested over $600 million in the field.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The first commercial gene therapy, Gendicine, was approved in China in 2003, for the treatment of certain cancers.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In 2011, Neovasculgen was registered in Russia as the first-in-class gene-therapy drug for treatment of peripheral artery disease, including critical limb ischemia.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In 2012, alipogene tiparvovec, a treatment for a rare inherited disorder, lipoprotein lipase deficiency, became the first treatment to be approved for clinical use in either the European Union or the United States after its endorsement by the European Commission.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Following early advances in genetic engineering of bacteria, cells, and small animals, scientists started considering how to apply it to medicine.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Two main approaches were considered – replacing or disrupting defective genes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Scientists focused on diseases caused by single-gene defects, such as cystic fibrosis, haemophilia, muscular dystrophy, thalassemia, and sickle cell anemia. alipogene tiparvovec treats one such disease, caused by a defect in lipoprotein lipase.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] DNA must be administered, reach the damaged cells, enter the cell and either express or disrupt a protein.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Multiple delivery techniques have been explored.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The initial approach incorporated DNA into an engineered virus to deliver the DNA into a chromosome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Naked DNA approaches have also been explored, especially in the context of vaccine development.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Generally, efforts focused on administering a gene that causes a needed protein to be expressed.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] More recently, increased understanding of nuclease function has led to more direct DNA editing, using techniques such as zinc finger nucleases and CRISPR.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The vector incorporates genes into chromosomes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The expressed nucleases then knock out and replace genes in the chromosome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] As of 2014 these approaches involve removing cells from patients, editing a chromosome and returning the transformed cells to patients.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Gene editing is a potential approach to alter the human genome to treat genetic diseases, viral diseases, and cancer.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] As of 2020 these approaches are being studied in clinical trials.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In 1986, a meeting at the Institute Of Medicine defined gene therapy as the addition or replacement of a gene in a targeted cell type.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In the same year, the FDA announced that it had jurisdiction over approving "gene therapy" without defining the term.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The FDA added a very broad definition in 1993 of any treatment that would 'modify or manipulate the expression of genetic material or to alter the biological properties of living cells'.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In 2018 this was narrowed to 'products that mediate their effects by transcription or translation of transferred genetic material or by specifically altering host (human) genetic sequences'.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] This definition would also exclude introducing cells that did not derive from a patient themselves, but include ex vivo approaches, and would not depend on the vector used.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Fact-checkers, such as Full Fact, Reuters, PolitiFact, and FactCheck.org said that calling the vaccines a gene therapy was incorrect.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Podcast host Joe Rogan was criticized for calling mRNA vaccines gene therapy as was British politician Andrew Bridgen, with fact checker Full Fact calling for Bridgen to be removed from the conservative party for this and other statements.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Gene therapy encapsulates many forms of adding different nucleic acids to a cell.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] *Gene augmentation* adds a new protein coding gene to a cell.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] One form of gene augmentation is *gene replacement therapy*, a treatment for monogenic recessive disorders where a single gene is not functional; an additional functional gene is added.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] For diseases caused by multiple genes or a dominant gene, gene silencing or gene editing approaches are more appropriate but *gene* *addition, a* form of gene augmentation where new gene is added, may improve a cell's function without modifying the genes that cause a disorder.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Gene therapy may be classified into two types by the type of cell it affects: somatic cell and germline gene therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In somatic cell gene therapy (SCGT), the therapeutic genes are transferred into any cell other than a gamete, germ cell, gametocyte, or undifferentiated stem cell.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Any such modifications affect the individual patient only, and are not inherited by offspring.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Somatic gene therapy represents mainstream basic and clinical research, in which therapeutic DNA (either integrated in the genome or as an external episome or plasmid) is used to treat disease.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Over 600 clinical trials utilizing SCGT are underway in the US.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Most focus on severe genetic disorders, including immunodeficiencies, haemophilia, thalassaemia, and cystic fibrosis.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Such single gene disorders are good candidates for somatic cell therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The complete correction of a genetic disorder or the replacement of multiple genes is not yet possible.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Only a few of the trials are in the advanced stages.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In germline gene therapy (GGT), germ cells (sperm or egg cells) are modified by the introduction of functional genes into their genomes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Modifying a germ cell causes all the organism's cells to contain the modified gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The change is therefore heritable and passed on to later generations.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Australia, Canada, Germany, Israel, Switzerland, and the Netherlands prohibit GGT for application in human beings, for technical and ethical reasons, including insufficient knowledge about possible risks to future generations and higher risks versus SCGT.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The US has no federal controls specifically addressing human genetic modification (beyond FDA regulations for therapies in general).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In *in vivo* gene therapy, a vector (typically, a virus) is introduced to the patient, which then achieves the desired biological effect by passing the genetic material (e.g. for a missing protein) into the patient's cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In *ex vivo* gene therapies, such as CAR-T therapeutics, the patient's own cells (autologous) or healthy donor cells (allogeneic) are modified outside the body (hence, *ex vivo*) using a vector to express a particular protein, such as a chimeric antigen receptor.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The concept of gene therapy is to fix a genetic problem at its source.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] If, for instance, a mutation in a certain gene causes the production of a dysfunctional protein resulting (usually recessively) in an inherited disease, gene therapy could be used to deliver a copy of this gene that does not contain the deleterious mutation and thereby produces a functional protein.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] This strategy is referred to as gene replacement therapy and could be employed to treat inherited retinal diseases.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] While the concept of gene replacement therapy is mostly suitable for recessive diseases, novel strategies have been suggested that are capable of also treating conditions with a dominant pattern of inheritance.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In vivo, gene editing systems using CRISPR have been used in studies with mice to treat cancer and have been effective at reducing tumors.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In vitro, the CRISPR system has been used to treat HPV cancer tumors.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Adeno-associated virus, Lentivirus based vectors have been to introduce the genome for the CRISPR system.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The delivery of DNA into cells can be accomplished by multiple methods.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The two major classes are recombinant viruses (sometimes called biological nanoparticles or viral vectors) and naked DNA or DNA complexes (non-viral methods).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In order to replicate, viruses introduce their genetic material into the host cell, tricking the host's cellular machinery into using it as blueprints for viral proteins.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Retroviruses go a stage further by having their genetic material copied into the nuclear genome of the host cell.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Scientists exploit this by substituting part of a virus's genetic material with therapeutic DNA or RNA.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Like the genetic material (DNA or RNA) in viruses, therapeutic genetic material can be designed to simply serve as a temporary blueprint that degrades naturally, as in a *non-integrative vectors*, or to enter the host's nucleus becoming a permanent part of the host's nuclear DNA in infected cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] A number of viruses have been used for human gene therapy, including viruses such as lentivirus, adenoviruses, herpes simplex, vaccinia, and adeno-associated virus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Adenovirus viral vectors (Ad) temporarily modify a cell's genetic expression with genetic material that is not integrated into the host cell's DNA.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] As of 2017, such vectors were used in 20% of trials for gene therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Adenovirus vectors are mostly used in cancer treatments and novel genetic vaccines such as the Ebola vaccine, vaccines used in clinical trials for HIV and SARS-CoV-2, or cancer vaccines.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Lentiviral vectors based on lentivirus, a retrovirus, can modify a cell's nuclear genome to permanently express a gene, although vectors can be modified to prevent integration.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Retroviruses were used in 18% of trials before 2018.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Libmeldy is an ex vivo stem cell treatment for metachromatic leukodystrophy which uses a lentiviral vector and was authorized by the European medical agency in 2020.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Adeno-associated virus (AAV) is a virus that is incapable of transmission between cells unless the cell is infected by another virus, a helper virus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Adenovirus and the herpes viruses act as helper viruses for AAV.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] AAV persists within the cell outside of the cell's nuclear genome for an extended period of time through the formation of concatemers mostly organized as episomes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Genetic material from AAV vectors is integrated into the host cell's nuclear genome at a low frequency and likely mediated by the DNA-modifying enzymes of the host cell.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Animal models suggest that integration of AAV genetic material into the host cell's nuclear genome may cause hepatocellular carcinoma, a form of liver cancer.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Several AAV investigational agents have been explored in treatment of wet age related macular degeneration by both intravitreal and subretinal approaches as a potential application of AAV gene therapy for human disease.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Non-viral vectors for gene therapy present certain advantages over viral methods, such as large scale production and low host immunogenicity.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] However, non-viral methods initially produced lower levels of transfection and gene expression, and thus lower therapeutic efficacy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Newer technologies offer promise of solving these problems, with the advent of increased cell-specific targeting and subcellular trafficking control.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Methods for non-viral gene therapy include the injection of naked DNA, electroporation, the gene gun, sonoporation, magnetofection, the use of oligonucleotides, lipoplexes, dendrimers, and inorganic nanoparticles.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] These therapeutics can be administered directly or through scaffold enrichment.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] More recent approaches, such as those performed by companies such as Ligandal, offer the possibility of creating cell-specific targeting technologies for a variety of gene therapy modalities, including RNA, DNA and gene editing tools such as CRISPR.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Other companies, such as Arbutus Biopharma and Arcturus Therapeutics, offer non-viral, non-cell-targeted approaches that mainly exhibit liver trophism.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In more recent years, startups such as Sixfold Bio, Nanite, GenEdit, and Spotlight Therapeutics have begun to solve the non-viral gene delivery problem.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Non-viral techniques offer the possibility of repeat dosing and greater tailorability of genetic payloads, which in the future will be more likely to take over viral-based delivery systems.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] These companies focus on gene editing, and still face major delivery hurdles.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] BioNTech, Moderna Therapeutics and CureVac focus on delivery of mRNA payloads, which are necessarily non-viral delivery problems.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Alnylam, Dicerna Pharmaceuticals, and Ionis Pharmaceuticals focus on delivery of siRNA (antisense oligonucleotides) for gene suppression, which also necessitate non-viral delivery systems.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In academic contexts, a number of laboratories are working on delivery of PEGylated particles, which form serum protein coronas and chiefly exhibit LDL receptor mediated uptake in cells *in vivo*.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] There have been attempts to treat cancer using gene therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] As of 2017, 65% of gene therapy trials were for cancer treatment.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Adenovirus vectors are useful for some cancer gene therapies because adenovirus can transiently insert genetic material into a cell without permanently altering the cell's nuclear genome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] These vectors can be used to cause antigens to be added to cancers causing an immune response, or hinder angiogenesis by expressing certain proteins.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] An Adenovirus vector is used in the commercial products Gendicine and Oncorine.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Another commercial product, Rexin G, uses a retrovirus-based vector and selectively binds to receptors that are more expressed in tumors.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] One approach, suicide gene therapy, works by introducing genes encoding enzymes that will cause a cancer cell to die.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Another approach is the use oncolytic viruses, such as Oncorine, which are viruses that selectively reproduce in cancerous cells leaving other cells unaffected.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] mRNA has been suggested as a non-viral vector for cancer gene therapy that would temporarily change a cancerous cell's function to create antigens or kill the cancerous cells and there have been several trials.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Afamitresgene autoleucel, sold under the brand name Tecelra, is an autologous T cell immunotherapy used for the treatment of synovial sarcoma.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] It is a T cell receptor (TCR) gene therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] It is the first FDA-approved engineered cell therapy for a solid tumor.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] It uses a self-inactivating lentiviral vector to express a T-cell receptor specific for MAGE-A4, a melanoma-associated antigen.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Gene therapy approaches to replace a faulty gene with a healthy gene have been proposed and are being studied for treating some genetic diseases.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] As of 2017, 11.1% of gene therapy clinical trials targeted monogenic diseases.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Diseases such as sickle cell disease that are caused by autosomal recessive disorders for which a person's normal phenotype or cell function may be restored in cells that have the disease by a normal copy of the gene that is mutated, may be a good candidate for gene therapy treatment.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The risks and benefits related to gene therapy for sickle cell disease are not known.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The eye is especially suitable for adeno-associated virus vectors.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] As of 2017, 7% of genetic therapy trials targeted infectious diseases.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] 69.2% of trials targeted HIV, 11% hepatitis B or C, and 7.1% malaria.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Companies operating in this field include Aldevron, Cobra Biologics and 3PBIOVIAN.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Three patients' deaths have been reported in gene therapy trials, putting the field under close scrutiny.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The first was that of Jesse Gelsinger, who died in 1999, because of immune rejection response.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] One X-SCID patient died of leukemia in 2003.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In 2007, a rheumatoid arthritis patient died from an infection; the subsequent investigation concluded that the death was not related to gene therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Regulations covering genetic modification are part of general guidelines about human-involved biomedical research.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] There are no international treaties which are legally binding in this area, but there are recommendations for national laws from various bodies.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The Helsinki Declaration (Ethical Principles for Medical Research Involving Human Subjects) was amended by the World Medical Association's General Assembly in 2008.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] This document provides principles physicians and researchers must consider when involving humans as research subjects.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The Statement on Gene Therapy Research initiated by the Human Genome Organization (HUGO) in 2001, provides a legal baseline for all countries.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] HUGO's document emphasizes human freedom and adherence to human rights, and offers recommendations for somatic gene therapy, including the importance of recognizing public concerns about such research.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] No federal legislation lays out protocols or restrictions about human genetic engineering.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] This subject is governed by overlapping regulations from local and federal agencies, including the Department of Health and Human Services, the FDA and NIH's Recombinant DNA Advisory Committee.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Researchers seeking federal funds for an investigational new drug application, (commonly the case for somatic human genetic engineering,) must obey international and federal guidelines for the protection of human subjects.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] NIH serves as the main gene therapy regulator for federally funded research.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Privately funded research is advised to follow these regulations.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] NIH provides funding for research that develops or enhances genetic engineering techniques and to evaluate the ethics and quality in current research.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The NIH maintains a mandatory registry of human genetic engineering research protocols that includes all federally funded projects.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] An NIH advisory committee published a set of guidelines on gene manipulation.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The guidelines discuss lab safety as well as human test subjects and various experimental types that involve genetic changes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Several sections specifically pertain to human genetic engineering, including Section III-C-1.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] This section describes required review processes and other aspects when seeking approval to begin clinical research involving genetic transfer into a human patient.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] The protocol for a gene therapy clinical trial must be approved by the NIH's Recombinant DNA Advisory Committee prior to any clinical trial beginning; this is different from any other kind of clinical trial.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] As with other kinds of drugs, the FDA regulates the quality and safety of gene therapy products and supervises how these products are used clinically.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Therapeutic alteration of the human genome falls under the same regulatory requirements as any other medical treatment.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Research involving human subjects, such as clinical trials, must be reviewed and approved by the FDA and an Institutional Review Board.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Athletes may adopt gene therapy technologies to improve their performance.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Gene doping is not known to occur, but multiple gene therapies may have such effects.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Kayser et al. argue that gene doping could level the playing field if all athletes receive equal access.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Critics claim that any therapeutic intervention for non-therapeutic/enhancement purposes compromises the ethical foundations of medicine and sports.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Genetic engineering could be used to cure diseases, but also to change physical appearance, metabolism, and even improve physical capabilities and mental faculties such as memory and intelligence.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Ethical claims about germline engineering include beliefs that every fetus has a right to remain genetically unmodified, that parents hold the right to genetically modify their offspring, and that every child has the right to be born free of preventable diseases.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] For parents, genetic engineering could be seen as another child enhancement technique to add to diet, exercise, education, training, cosmetics, and plastic surgery.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Another theorist claims that moral concerns limit but do not prohibit germline engineering.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] A 2020 issue of the journal *Bioethics* was devoted to moral issues surrounding germline genetic engineering in people.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] Possible regulatory schemes include a complete ban, provision to everyone, or professional self-regulation.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] As early in the history of biotechnology as 1990, there have been scientists opposed to attempts to modify the human germline using these new tools, and such concerns have continued as technology progressed.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] With the advent of new techniques like CRISPR, in March 2015 a group of scientists urged a worldwide moratorium on clinical use of gene editing technologies to edit the human genome in a way that can be inherited.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p01] In April 2015, researchers sparked controversy when they reported results of basic research to edit the DNA of non-viable human embryos using CRISPR.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In 1972, Friedmann and Roblin authored a paper in *Science* titled "Gene therapy for human genetic disease?".
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Rogers (1970) was cited for proposing that *exogenous good DNA* be used to replace the defective DNA in those with genetic defects.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In 1984, a retrovirus vector system was designed that could efficiently insert foreign genes into mammalian chromosomes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The first approved gene therapy clinical research in the US took place in September 1990, at the National Institutes of Health (NIH), under the direction of William French Anderson.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Four-year-old Ashanti DeSilva received treatment for a genetic defect that left her with adenosine deaminase deficiency (ADA-SCID), a severe immune system deficiency.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The defective gene of the patient's blood cells was replaced by the functional variant.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Ashanti's immune system was partially restored by the therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Production of the missing enzyme was temporarily stimulated, but the new cells with functional genes were not generated.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] She led a normal life only with the regular injections performed every two months.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The effects were successful, but temporary.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Cancer gene therapy was introduced in 1992/93 (Trojan et al.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The treatment of glioblastoma multiforme, the malignant brain tumor whose outcome is always fatal, was done using a vector expressing antisense IGF-I RNA (clinical trial approved by NIH protocol no.1602 24 November 1993, and by the FDA in 1994).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] This therapy also represents the beginning of cancer immunogene therapy, a treatment which proves to be effective due to the anti-tumor mechanism of IGF-I antisense, which is related to strong immune and apoptotic phenomena.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In 1992, Claudio Bordignon, working at the Vita-Salute San Raffaele University, performed the first gene therapy procedure using hematopoietic stem cells as vectors to deliver genes intended to correct hereditary diseases.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In 2002, this work led to the publication of the first successful gene therapy treatment for ADA-SCID.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The success of a multi-center trial for treating children with SCID (severe combined immune deficiency or "bubble boy" disease) from 2000 and 2002, was questioned when two of the ten children treated at the trial's Paris center developed a leukemia-like condition.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Clinical trials were halted temporarily in 2002, but resumed after regulatory review of the protocol in the US, the United Kingdom, France, Italy, and Germany.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In 1993, Andrew Gobea was born with SCID following prenatal genetic screening.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Blood was removed from his mother's placenta and umbilical cord immediately after birth, to acquire stem cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The allele that codes for adenosine deaminase (ADA) was obtained and inserted into a retrovirus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Retroviruses and stem cells were mixed, after which the viruses inserted the gene into the stem cell chromosomes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Stem cells containing the working ADA gene were injected into Andrew's blood.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Injections of the ADA enzyme were also given weekly.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] For four years T cells (white blood cells), produced by stem cells, made ADA enzymes using the ADA gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] After four years more treatment was needed.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In 1996, Luigi Naldini and Didier Trono developed a new class of gene therapy vectors based on HIV capable of infecting non-dividing cells that have since then been widely used in clinical and research settings, pioneering lentivirals vector in gene therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Jesse Gelsinger's death in 1999 impeded gene therapy research in the US.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] As a result, the FDA suspended several clinical trials pending the reevaluation of ethical and procedural practices.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The modified gene therapy strategy of antisense IGF-I RNA (NIH n˚ 1602) using antisense / triple helix anti-IGF-I approach was registered in 2002, by Wiley gene therapy clinical trial - n˚ 635 and 636.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The approach has shown promising results in the treatment of six different malignant tumors: glioblastoma, cancers of liver, colon, prostate, uterus, and ovary (Collaborative NATO Science Programme on Gene Therapy USA, France, Poland n˚ LST 980517 conducted by J.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] This anti-gene antisense/triple helix therapy has proven to be efficient, due to the mechanism stopping simultaneously IGF-I expression on translation and transcription levels, strengthening anti-tumor immune and apoptotic phenomena.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Sickle cell disease can be treated in mice.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The mice – which have essentially the same defect that causes human cases – used a viral vector to induce production of fetal hemoglobin (HbF), which normally ceases to be produced shortly after birth.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In humans, the use of hydroxyurea to stimulate the production of HbF temporarily alleviates sickle cell symptoms.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The researchers demonstrated this treatment to be a more permanent means to increase therapeutic HbF production.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] A new gene therapy approach repaired errors in messenger RNA derived from defective genes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] This technique has the potential to treat thalassaemia, cystic fibrosis and some cancers.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Researchers created liposomes 25 nanometers across that can carry therapeutic DNA through pores in the nuclear membrane.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In 2003, a research team inserted genes into the brain for the first time.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] They used liposomes coated in a polymer called polyethylene glycol, which unlike viral vectors, are small enough to cross the blood–brain barrier.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Short pieces of double-stranded RNA (short, interfering RNAs or siRNAs) are used by cells to degrade RNA of a particular sequence.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] If a siRNA is designed to match the RNA copied from a faulty gene, then the abnormal protein product of that gene will not be produced.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Gendicine is a cancer gene therapy that delivers the tumor suppressor gene p53 using an engineered adenovirus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In 2003, it was approved in China for the treatment of head and neck squamous cell carcinoma.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In March, researchers announced the successful use of gene therapy to treat two adult patients for X-linked chronic granulomatous disease, a disease which affects myeloid cells and damages the immune system.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The study is the first to show that gene therapy can treat the myeloid system.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In May, a team reported a way to prevent the immune system from rejecting a newly delivered gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Similar to organ transplantation, gene therapy has been plagued by this problem.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The immune system normally recognizes the new gene as foreign and rejects the cells carrying it.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The research utilized a newly uncovered network of genes regulated by molecules known as microRNAs.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] This natural function selectively obscured their therapeutic gene in immune system cells and protected it from discovery.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Mice infected with the gene containing an immune-cell microRNA target sequence did not reject the gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In August, scientists successfully treated metastatic melanoma in two patients using killer T cells genetically retargeted to attack the cancer cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In November, researchers reported on the use of VRX496, a gene-based immunotherapy for the treatment of HIV that uses a lentiviral vector to deliver an antisense gene against the HIV envelope.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In a phase I clinical trial, five subjects with chronic HIV infection who had failed to respond to at least two antiretroviral regimens were treated.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] A single intravenous infusion of autologous CD4 T cells genetically modified with VRX496 was well tolerated.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] All patients had stable or decreased viral load; four of the five patients had stable or increased CD4 T cell counts.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] All five patients had stable or increased immune response to HIV antigens and other pathogens.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] This was the first evaluation of a lentiviral vector administered in a US human clinical trial.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In May 2007, researchers announced the first gene therapy trial for inherited retinal disease.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The first operation was carried out on a 23-year-old British male, Robert Johnson, in early 2007.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Leber's congenital amaurosis is an inherited blinding disease caused by mutations in the RPE65 gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The results of a small clinical trial in children were published in April.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Delivery of recombinant adeno-associated virus (AAV) carrying RPE65 yielded positive results.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In May, two more groups reported positive results in independent clinical trials using gene therapy to treat the condition.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In all three clinical trials, patients recovered functional vision without apparent side-effects.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In September researchers were able to give trichromatic vision to squirrel monkeys.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In November 2009, researchers halted a fatal genetic disorder called adrenoleukodystrophy in two children using a lentivirus vector to deliver a functioning version of ABCD1, the gene that is mutated in the disorder.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] An April paper reported that gene therapy addressed achromatopsia (color blindness) in dogs by targeting cone photoreceptors.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Cone function and day vision were restored for at least 33 months in two young specimens.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The therapy was less efficient for older dogs.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In September it was announced that an 18-year-old male patient in France with beta thalassemia major had been successfully treated.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Beta thalassemia major is an inherited blood disease in which beta haemoglobin is missing and patients are dependent on regular lifelong blood transfusions.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The technique used a lentiviral vector to transduce the human β-globin gene into purified blood and marrow cells obtained from the patient in June 2007.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The patient's haemoglobin levels were stable at 9 to 10 g/dL.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] About a third of the hemoglobin contained the form introduced by the viral vector and blood transfusions were not needed.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Bone marrow transplants are the only cure for thalassemia, but 75% of patients do not find a matching donor.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Cancer immunogene therapy using modified antigene, antisense/triple helix approach was introduced in South America in 2010/11 in La Sabana University, Bogota (Ethical Committee 14 December 2010, no P-004-10).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Considering the ethical aspect of gene diagnostic and gene therapy targeting IGF-I, the IGF-I expressing tumors i.e. lung and epidermis cancers were treated (Trojan et al.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In 2007 and 2008, a man (Timothy Ray Brown) was cured of HIV by repeated hematopoietic stem cell transplantation (see also allogeneic stem cell transplantation, allogeneic bone marrow transplantation, allotransplantation) with double-delta-32 mutation which disables the CCR5 receptor.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] This cure was accepted by the medical community in 2011.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] It required complete ablation of existing bone marrow, which is very debilitating.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In August two of three subjects of a pilot study were confirmed to have been cured from chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The therapy used genetically modified T cells to attack cells that expressed the CD19 protein to fight the disease.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In 2013, the researchers announced that 26 of 59 patients had achieved complete remission and the original patient had remained tumor-free.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Human HGF plasmid DNA therapy of cardiomyocytes is being examined as a potential treatment for coronary artery disease as well as treatment for the damage that occurs to the heart after myocardial infarction.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In 2011, Neovasculgen was registered in Russia as the first-in-class gene-therapy drug for treatment of peripheral artery disease, including critical limb ischemia; it delivers the gene encoding for VEGF.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Neovasculogen is a plasmid encoding the CMV promoter and the 165 amino acid form of VEGF.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The FDA approved Phase I clinical trials on thalassemia major patients in the US for 10 participants in July.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The study was expected to continue until 2015.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In July 2012, the European Medicines Agency recommended approval of a gene therapy treatment for the first time in either Europe or the United States.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The treatment used Alipogene tiparvovec (Glybera) to compensate for lipoprotein lipase deficiency, which can cause severe pancreatitis.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The recommendation was endorsed by the European Commission in November 2012, and commercial rollout began in late 2014.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Alipogene tiparvovec was expected to cost around $1.6 million per treatment in 2012, revised to $1 million in 2015, making it the most expensive medicine in the world at the time.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] As of 2016, only the patients treated in clinical trials and a patient who paid the full price for treatment have received the drug.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In December 2012, it was reported that 10 of 13 patients with multiple myeloma were in remission "or very close to it" three months after being injected with a treatment involving genetically engineered T cells to target proteins NY-ESO-1 and LAGE-1, which exist only on cancerous myeloma cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In March researchers reported that three of five adult subjects who had acute lymphocytic leukemia (ALL) had been in remission for five months to two years after being treated with genetically modified T cells which attacked cells with CD19 genes on their surface, i.e. all B cells, cancerous or not.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The researchers believed that the patients' immune systems would make normal T cells and B cells after a couple of months.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] One patient relapsed and died and one died of a blood clot unrelated to the disease.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Following encouraging Phase I trials, in April, researchers announced they were starting Phase II clinical trials (called CUPID2 and SERCA-LVAD) on 250 patients at several hospitals to combat heart disease.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The therapy was designed to increase the levels of SERCA2, a protein in heart muscles, improving muscle function.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) granted this a breakthrough therapy designation to accelerate the trial and approval process.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In 2016, it was reported that no improvement was found from the CUPID 2 trial.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In July researchers reported promising results for six children with two severe hereditary diseases had been treated with a partially deactivated lentivirus to replace a faulty gene and after 7–32 months.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Three of the children had metachromatic leukodystrophy, which causes children to lose cognitive and motor skills.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The other children had Wiskott–Aldrich syndrome, which leaves them to open to infection, autoimmune diseases, and cancer.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Follow up trials with gene therapy on another six children with Wiskott–Aldrich syndrome were also reported as promising.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In October researchers reported that two children born with adenosine deaminase severe combined immunodeficiency disease (ADA-SCID) had been treated with genetically engineered stem cells 18 months previously and that their immune systems were showing signs of full recovery.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Another three children were making progress.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In 2014, a further 18 children with ADA-SCID were cured by gene therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] ADA-SCID children have no functioning immune system and are sometimes known as "bubble children".
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Also in October researchers reported that they had treated six people with haemophilia in early 2011 using an adeno-associated virus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Over two years later all six were producing clotting factor.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In January researchers reported that six choroideremia patients had been treated with adeno-associated virus with a copy of REP1.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Over a six-month to two-year period all had improved their sight.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] By 2016, 32 patients had been treated with positive results and researchers were hopeful the treatment would be long-lasting.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Choroideremia is an inherited genetic eye disease with no approved treatment, leading to loss of sight.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In March researchers reported that 12 HIV patients had been treated since 2009 in a trial with a genetically engineered virus with a rare mutation (CCR5 deficiency) known to protect against HIV with promising results.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Clinical trials of gene therapy for sickle cell disease were started in 2014.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In February LentiGlobin BB305, a gene therapy treatment undergoing clinical trials for treatment of beta thalassemia gained FDA "breakthrough" status after several patients were able to forgo the frequent blood transfusions usually required to treat the disease.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In March researchers delivered a recombinant gene encoding a broadly neutralizing antibody into monkeys infected with simian HIV; the monkeys' cells produced the antibody, which cleared them of HIV.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The technique is named immunoprophylaxis by gene transfer (IGT).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Animal tests for antibodies to ebola, malaria, influenza, and hepatitis were underway.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In December, scientists of major world academies called for a moratorium on inheritable human genome edits, including those related to CRISPR-Cas9 technologies but that basic research including embryo gene editing should continue.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Researchers successfully treated a boy with epidermolysis bullosa using skin grafts grown from his own skin cells, genetically altered to repair the mutation that caused his disease.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In November, researchers announced that they had treated a baby girl, Layla Richards, with an experimental treatment using donor T cells genetically engineered using TALEN to attack cancer cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] One year after the treatment she was still free of her cancer (a highly aggressive form of acute lymphoblastic leukaemia [ALL]).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Children with highly aggressive ALL normally have a very poor prognosis and Layla's disease had been regarded as terminal before the treatment.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In April the Committee for Medicinal Products for Human Use of the European Medicines Agency endorsed a gene therapy treatment called Strimvelis and the European Commission approved it in June.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] This treats children born with adenosine deaminase deficiency and who have no functioning immune system.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] This was the second gene therapy treatment to be approved in Europe.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In October, Chinese scientists reported they had started a trial to genetically modify T cells from 10 adult patients with lung cancer and reinject the modified T cells back into their bodies to attack the cancer cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The T cells had the PD-1 protein (which stops or slows the immune response) removed using CRISPR-Cas9.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] A 2016 Cochrane systematic review looking at data from four trials on topical cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator (CFTR) gene therapy does not support its clinical use as a mist inhaled into the lungs to treat cystic fibrosis patients with lung infections.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] One of the four trials did find weak evidence that liposome-based CFTR gene transfer therapy may lead to a small respiratory improvement for people with CF.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] This weak evidence is not enough to make a clinical recommendation for routine CFTR gene therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In February Kite Pharma announced results from a clinical trial of CAR-T cells in around a hundred people with advanced non-Hodgkin lymphoma.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In March, French scientists reported on clinical research of gene therapy to treat sickle cell disease.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In August, the FDA approved tisagenlecleucel for acute lymphoblastic leukemia.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The T cells are engineered to target a protein called CD19 that is common on B cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] This is the first form of gene therapy to be approved in the United States.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In October, a similar therapy called axicabtagene ciloleucel was approved for non-Hodgkin lymphoma.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In October, biophysicist and biohacker Josiah Zayner claimed to have performed the very first in-vivo human genome editing in the form of a self-administered therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] On 13 November, medical scientists working with Sangamo Therapeutics, headquartered in Richmond, California, announced the first ever in-body human gene editing therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The treatment, designed to permanently insert a healthy version of the flawed gene that causes Hunter syndrome, was given to 44-year-old Brian Madeux and is part of the world's first study to permanently edit DNA inside the human body.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The success of the gene insertion was later confirmed.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Clinical trials by Sangamo involving gene editing using zinc finger nuclease (ZFN) are ongoing.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In December the results of using an adeno-associated virus with blood clotting factor VIII to treat nine haemophilia A patients were published.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Six of the seven patients on the high dose regime increased the level of the blood clotting VIII to normal levels.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The low and medium dose regimes had no effect on the patient's blood clotting levels.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In December, the FDA approved voretigene neparvovec, the first *in vivo* gene therapy, for the treatment of blindness due to Leber's congenital amaurosis.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The price of this treatment is US$850,000 for both eyes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In May, the FDA approved onasemnogene abeparvovec (Zolgensma) for treating spinal muscular atrophy in children under two years of age.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The list price of Zolgensma was set at US$2.125 million per dose, making it the most expensive drug ever.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In May, the EMA approved betibeglogene autotemcel (Zynteglo) for treating beta thalassemia for people twelve years of age and older.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In July, Allergan and Editas Medicine announced phase I/II clinical trial of AGN-151587 for the treatment of Leber congenital amaurosis 10.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] This is one of the first studies of a CRISPR-based *in vivo* human gene editing therapy, where the editing takes place inside the human body.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The first injection of the CRISPR-Cas System was confirmed in March 2020.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Exagamglogene autotemcel, a CRISPR-based human gene editing therapy, was used for sickle cell and thalassemia in clinical trials.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In May, onasemnogene abeparvovec (Zolgensma) was approved by the European Union for the treatment of spinal muscular atrophy in people who either have clinical symptoms of SMA type 1 or who have no more than three copies of the *SMN2* gene, irrespective of body weight or age.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In August, Audentes Therapeutics reported that three out of 17 children with X-linked myotubular myopathy participating the clinical trial of a AAV8-based gene therapy treatment AT132 have died.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] It was suggested that the treatment, whose dosage is based on body weight, exerts a disproportionately toxic effect on heavier patients, since the three patients who died were heavier than the others.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The trial has been put on clinical hold.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The active substance of Libmeldy consists of the child's own stem cells which have been modified to contain working copies of the ARSA gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] When the modified cells are injected back into the patient as a one-time infusion, the cells are expected to start producing the ARSA enzyme that breaks down the build-up of sulfatides in the nerve cells and other cells of the patient's body.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Libmeldy was approved for medical use in the EU in December 2020.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] On 15 October, Lysogene, a French biotechnological company, reported the death of a patient in who has received LYS-SAF302, an experimental gene therapy treatment for mucopolysaccharidosis type IIIA (Sanfilippo syndrome type A).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In July results of a small gene therapy phase I study was published reporting observation of dopamine restoration on seven patients between 4 and 9 years old affected by aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase deficiency (AADC deficiency).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In February, the first ever gene therapy for Tay–Sachs disease was announced, it uses an adeno-associated virus to deliver the correct instruction for the HEXA gene on brain cells which causes the disease.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] Only two children were part of a compassionate trial presenting improvements over the natural course of the disease and no vector-related adverse events.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In May, eladocagene exuparvovec is recommended for approval by the European Commission.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The procedure included reprogramming a healthy T-cell to destroy the cancerous T-cells to first rid her of leukaemia, and then rebuilding her immune system using healthy immune cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] The GOSH team used BASE editing and had previously treated a case of acute lymphoblastic leukaemia in 2015 using TALENs.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] One trial found 65% of the Vyjuvek-treated wounds completely closed while only 26% of the placebo-treated at 24 weeks.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] It has been also reported its use as an eyedrop for a patient with DEB that had vision loss due to the widespread blistering with good results.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In July 2023, it was reported that it had been developed a new method to affect genetic expressions through direct current.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In December 2023, two gene therapies were approved for sickle cell disease, exagamglogene autotemcel and lovotibeglogene autotemcel.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] In November 2024, FDA granted accelerated approval for eladocagene exuparvovec-tneq (Kebilidi, PTC Therapeutics), a direct-to-brain gene therapy for aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase deficiency.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] It uses a recombinant adeno-associated virus serotype 2 (rAAV2) to deliver a functioning DOPA decarboxylase (DDC) gene directly into the putamen, increasing the AADC enzyme and restoring dopamine production.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/gene-therapy-p02] It is administered through a stereotactic surgical procedure.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Lentiviruses can integrate a significant amount of viral complementary DNA into the DNA of the host cell and can efficiently infect nondividing cells, so they are one of the most efficient methods of gene delivery.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] They can become endogenous, integrating their genome into the host germline genome, so that the virus is henceforth inherited by the host's descendants.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Five serogroups of lentiviruses are recognized, reflecting the vertebrate hosts with which they are associated (primates, sheep and goats, horses, domestic cats, and cattle).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] The primate lentiviruses are distinguished by the use of CD4 protein as a receptor and the absence of dUTPase.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] The virions are enveloped viruses 80–100 nm in diameter.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] They are spherical or pleomorphic, with capsid cores that mature to a cylindrical or conical shape.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Projections of envelope make the surface appear rough, or tiny spikes (about 8 nm) may be dispersed evenly over the surface.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Lentiviruses contain 2 positive sense, single-strand RNAs that are bound by nucleocapsid proteins.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] As with all retroviruses, lentiviruses have *gag*, *pol* and *env* genes, coding for viral proteins in the order: 5´-*gag*-*pol*-*env*-3´.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Unlike other retroviruses, however, lentiviruses have two regulatory genes, *tat* and *rev*.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] They may also have additional accessory genes depending on the virus (e.g., for HIV-1: *vif*, *vpr*, *vpu*, *nef*) whose products are involved in regulation of synthesis and processing viral RNA and other replicative functions.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] The long terminal repeat (LTR) is about 600 nt long, of which the U3 region is 450, the R sequence 100 and the U5 region some 70 nt long.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Retroviruses carry proteins within their capsids, which bind the RNA genome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] These proteins are typically involved in the early stages of genome replication, and include reverse transcriptase and integrase.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Reverse transcriptase uses the viral RNA genome as a template for the synthesis of a complementary DNA copy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Reverse transcriptase possesses [RNase H] activity for destruction of the RNA-template.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Integrase binds both the viral cDNA generated by reverse transcriptase and the host DNA.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Tat acts as a trans-activator during transcription to enhance initiation and elongation.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] The Rev responsive element acts post-transcriptionally, regulating mRNA splicing and transport to the cytoplasm.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] The lentiviral proteome consists of five major structural proteins and three or four non-structural proteins.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Primate lentiviruses lack the dUTPase, so they have three non-structural proteins, whereas all other lentiviruses encode it.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Gp41 transmembrane envelope protein TM, also encoded by the viral gene *env*.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] P24 capsid protein CA, encoded by the viral gene *gag*.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] P17 matrix protein MA, also encoded by *gag*.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] P7/P9 capsid protein NC, also encoded by *gag*.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] The envelope proteins SU and TM are glycosylated in at least some lentiviruses (HIV, SIV), if not all of them.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Glycosylation seems to play a structural role in the concealment and variation of antigenic sites necessary for the host to mount an immune system response.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Integrase IN also encoded by the *pol* gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Protease PR encoded by the *pro* gene (part of *pol* gene in some viruses).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] 4. dUTPase DU encoded by the *pro* gene (part of *pol* gene in some viruses), the role of which is still unknown.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Serological relationships: Antigen determinants are type specific and group specific.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Antigen determinants that possess type-specific reactivity are found on the envelope.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Antigen determinants that possess type-specific reactivity and are involved in antibody mediated neutralization are found on the glycoproteins.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Cross-reactivity has been found among some species of the same serotype, but not between members of different genera.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Classification of members of this taxon is infrequently based on their antigenic properties.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Lentivirus is primarily a research tool used to introduce a gene product into in vitro systems or animal models.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Large-scale collaborative efforts are underway to use lentiviruses to block the expression of a specific gene using RNA interference technology in high-throughput formats.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Conversely, lentivirus are also used to stably over-express certain genes, thus allowing researchers to examine the effect of increased gene expression in a model system.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Another common application is to use a lentivirus to introduce a new gene into human or animal cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] For example, a model of mouse hemophilia is corrected by expressing wild-type platelet-factor VIII, the gene that is mutated in human hemophilia.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Lentiviral infection has advantages over other gene-therapy methods including high-efficiency infection of dividing and non-dividing cells, long-term stable expression of a transgene, and low immunogenicity.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Lentiviruses have also been successfully used for transduction of diabetic mice with the gene encoding PDGF (platelet-derived growth factor), a therapy being considered for use in humans.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Finally, lentiviruses have been also used to elicit an immune response against tumor antigens.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] These treatments, like most current gene therapy experiments, show promise but are yet to be established as safe and effective in controlled human studies.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/lentivirus] Gammaretroviral and lentiviral vectors have so far been used in more than 300 clinical trials, addressing treatment options for various diseases.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] A **retrovirus** is a virus that inserts a DNA copy of its RNA genome into the DNA of a host cell that it invades, thus changing the genome of that cell.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] After invading a host cell's cytoplasm, the virus uses its own reverse transcriptase enzyme to produce DNA from its RNA genome, the reverse of the usual pattern, thus *retro* (backward).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The new DNA is then incorporated into the host cell genome by an integrase enzyme, at which point the retroviral DNA is referred to as a provirus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The host cell then treats the viral DNA as part of its own genome, transcribing and translating the viral genes along with the cell's own genes, producing the proteins required to assemble new copies of the virus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Many retroviruses cause serious diseases in humans, other mammals, and birds.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Retroviruses have many subfamilies in three basic groups.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The specialized DNA-infiltration enzymes in retroviruses make them valuable research tools in molecular biology, and they have been used successfully in gene delivery systems.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Evidence from endogenous retroviruses (inherited provirus DNA in animal genomes) suggests that retroviruses have been infecting vertebrates for at least 450 million years.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Virions, viruses in the form of independent particles of retroviruses, consist of enveloped particles about 100 nm in diameter.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The outer lipid envelope consists of glycoprotein.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The virions also contain two identical single-stranded RNA molecules 7–10 kilobases in length.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The two molecules are present as a dimer, formed by base pairing between complementary sequences.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Interaction sites between the two RNA molecules have been identified as a "kissing stem-loop".
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Although virions of different retroviruses do not have the same morphology or biology, all the virion components are very similar.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The retroviral genome is packaged as viral particles.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] These viral particles are dimers of single-stranded, positive-sense, linear RNA molecules.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Retroviruses (and orterviruses in general) follow a layout of 5'–*gag*–*pro*–*pol*–*env*–3' in the RNA genome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] *gag* and *pol* encode polyproteins, each managing the capsid and replication.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The *pol* region encodes enzymes necessary for viral replication, such as reverse transcriptase, protease and integrase.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Depending on the virus, the genes may overlap or fuse into larger polyprotein chains.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The lentivirus genus, the spumavirus genus, the HTLV / bovine leukemia virus (BLV) genus, and a newly introduced fish virus genus are retroviruses classified as complex.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] These viruses have genes called accessory genes, in addition to gag, pro, pol and env genes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Accessory genes are located between pol and env, downstream from the env, including the U3 region of LTR, or in the env and overlapping portions.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] While accessory genes have auxiliary roles, they also coordinate and regulate viral gene expression.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] In addition, some retroviruses may carry genes called oncogenes or onc genes from another class.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Retroviruses with these genes (also called transforming viruses) are known for their ability to quickly cause tumors in animals and transform cells in culture into an oncogenic state.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The polyproteins are cleaved into smaller proteins each with their own function.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The nucleotides encoding them are known as *subgenes*.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] When retroviruses have integrated their own genome into the germ line, their genome is passed on to a following generation.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] These endogenous retroviruses (ERVs), contrasted with exogenous ones, now make up 5–8% of the human genome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Most insertions have no known function and are often referred to as "junk DNA".
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] However, many endogenous retroviruses play important roles in host biology, such as control of gene transcription, cell fusion during placental development in the course of the germination of an embryo, and resistance to exogenous retroviral infection.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Endogenous retroviruses have also received special attention in the research of immunology-related pathologies, such as autoimmune diseases like multiple sclerosis, although endogenous retroviruses have not yet been proven to play any causal role in this class of disease.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] While transcription was classically thought to occur only from DNA to RNA, reverse transcriptase transcribes RNA into DNA.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The term "retro" in retrovirus refers to this reversal (making DNA from RNA) of the usual direction of transcription.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] It still obeys the central dogma of molecular biology, which states that information can be transferred from nucleic acid to nucleic acid but cannot be transferred back from protein to either protein or nucleic acid.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Reverse transcriptase activity outside of retroviruses has been found in almost all eukaryotes, enabling the generation and insertion of new copies of retrotransposons into the host genome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] These inserts are transcribed by enzymes of the host into new RNA molecules that enter the cytosol.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Next, some of these RNA molecules are translated into viral proteins.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The proteins encoded by the gag and pol genes are translated from genome-length mRNAs into Gag and Gag–Pol polyproteins.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] In example, for the *gag* gene; it is translated into molecules of the capsid protein, and for the *pol* gene; it is translated into molecules of reverse transcriptase.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Retroviruses need a lot more of the Gag proteins than the Pol proteins and have developed advanced systems to synthesize the required amount of each.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] As an example, after Gag synthesis nearly 95 percent of the ribosomes terminate translation, while other ribosomes continue translation to synthesize Gag–Pol.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] In the rough endoplasmic reticulum glycosylation begins and the *env* gene is translated from spliced mRNAs in the rough endoplasmic reticulum, into molecules of the envelope protein.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] When the envelope protein molecules are carried to the Golgi complex, they are divided into surface glycoprotein and transmembrane glycoprotein by a host protease.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] These two glycoprotein products stay in close affiliation, and they are transported to the plasma membrane after further glycosylation.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] A retrovirus must "bring" its own reverse transcriptase in its capsid, otherwise it is unable to utilize the enzymes of the infected cell to carry out the task, due to the unusual nature of producing DNA from RNA.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Industrial drugs that are designed as protease and reverse-transcriptase inhibitors are made such that they target specific sites and sequences within their respective enzymes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] However these drugs can quickly become ineffective due to the fact that the gene sequences that code for the protease and the reverse transcriptase quickly mutate.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] These changes in bases cause specific codons and sites with the enzymes to change and thereby avoid drug targeting by losing the sites that the drug actually targets.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Because reverse transcription lacks the usual proofreading of DNA replication, a retrovirus mutates very often.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] This enables the virus to grow resistant to antiviral pharmaceuticals quickly, and impedes the development of effective vaccines and inhibitors for the retrovirus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] One difficulty faced with some retroviruses, such as the Moloney retrovirus, involves the requirement for cells to be actively dividing for transduction.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] As a result, cells such as neurons are very resistant to infection and transduction by retroviruses.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] This gives rise to a concern that insertional mutagenesis due to integration into the host genome might lead to cancer or leukemia.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] This is unlike *Lentivirus*, a genus of *Retroviridae*, which are able to integrate their RNA into the genome of non-dividing host cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Two RNA genomes are packaged into each retrovirus particle, but, after an infection, each virus generates only one provirus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] After infection, reverse transcription occurs and this process is accompanied by recombination.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Recombination involves template strand switching between the two genome copies (copy choice recombination) during reverse transcription.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] From 5 to 14 recombination events per genome occur at each replication cycle.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Genetic recombination appears to be necessary for maintaining genome integrity and as a repair mechanism for salvaging damaged genomes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The DNA formed after reverse transcription (the provirus) is longer than the RNA genome because each of the terminals have the U3 - R - U5 sequences called long terminal repeat (LTR).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Thus, 5' terminal has the extra U3 sequence, while the other terminal has the U5 sequence.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] LTRs are able to send signals for vital tasks to be carried out such as initiation of RNA production or management of the rate of transcription.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] This way, LTRs can control replication, hence, the entire progress of the viral cycle.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Although located in the nucleus, the non-integrated retroviral cDNA is a very weak substrate for transcription.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] For this reason, an integrated provirus is a necessary for permanent and an effective expression of retroviral genes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] This DNA can be incorporated into host genome as a provirus that can be passed on to progeny cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The retrovirus DNA is inserted at random into the host genome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Because of this, it can be inserted into oncogenes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] In this way some retroviruses can convert normal cells into cancer cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Some provirus remains latent in the cell for a long period of time before it is activated by the change in cell environment.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Studies of retroviruses led to the first demonstrated synthesis of DNA from RNA templates, a fundamental mode for transferring genetic material that occurs in both eukaryotes and prokaryotes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] It has been speculated that the RNA to DNA transcription processes used by retroviruses may have first caused DNA to be used as genetic material.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] In this model, the RNA world hypothesis, cellular organisms adopted the more chemically stable DNA when retroviruses evolved to create DNA from the RNA templates.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] An estimate of the date of evolution of the foamy-like endogenous retroviruses placed the time of the most recent common ancestor at > 450 million years ago.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Gammaretroviral and lentiviral vectors for gene therapy have been developed that mediate stable genetic modification of treated cells by chromosomal integration of the transferred vector genomes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] This technology is of use, not only for research purposes, but also for clinical gene therapy aiming at the long-term correction of genetic defects, e.g., in stem and progenitor cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Retroviral vector particles with tropism for various target cells have been designed.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Retroviral mutations can be developed to make transgenic mouse models to study various cancers and their metastatic models.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Retroviruses that cause tumor growth include Rous sarcoma virus and mouse mammary tumor virus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Cancer can be triggered by proto-oncogenes that were mistakenly incorporated into proviral DNA or by the disruption of cellular proto-oncogenes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Rous sarcoma virus contains the src gene that triggers tumor formation.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Later it was found that a similar gene in cells is involved in cell signaling, which was most likely excised with the proviral DNA.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Nontransforming viruses can randomly insert their DNA into proto-oncogenes, disrupting the expression of proteins that regulate the cell cycle.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The promoter of the provirus DNA can also cause over expression of regulatory genes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Retroviruses can cause diseases such as cancer and immunodeficiency.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] If viral DNA is integrated into host chromosomes, it can lead to permanent infections.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] It is therefore important to discover the body's response to retroviruses.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Exogenous retroviruses are especially associated with pathogenic diseases.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] For example, mice have mouse mammary tumor virus (MMTV), which is a retrovirus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] This virus passes to newborn mice through mammary milk.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] When they are 6 months old, the mice carrying the virus get mammary cancer because of the retrovirus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] In addition, leukemia virus I (HTLV-1), found in human T cell, has been found in humans for many years.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] It is estimated that this retrovirus causes leukemia in the ages of 40 and 50.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] It has a replicable structure that can induce cancer.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] In addition to the usual gene sequence of retroviruses, HTLV-1 contains a fourth region, PX.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] This region encodes Tax, Rex, p12, p13 and p30 regulatory proteins.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The Tax protein initiates the leukemic process and organizes the transcription of all viral genes in the integrated HTLV proviral DNA.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Exogenous retroviruses are infectious RNA- or DNA-containing viruses that are transmitted from one organism to another.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] All members of Group VI use virally encoded reverse transcriptase, an RNA-dependent DNA polymerase, to produce DNA from the initial virion RNA genome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] This DNA is often integrated into the host genome, as in the case of retroviruses and pseudoviruses, where it is replicated and transcribed by the host.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The family *Retroviridae* was previously divided into three subfamilies (*Oncovirinae*, *Lentivirinae*, and *Spumavirinae*), but are now divided into two: *Orthoretrovirinae* and *Spumaretrovirinae*.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The term oncovirus is now commonly used to describe a cancer-causing virus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Both families in Group VII have DNA genomes contained within the invading virus particles.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] The DNA genome is transcribed into both mRNA, for use as a transcript in protein synthesis, and pre-genomic RNA, for use as the template during genome replication.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Virally encoded reverse transcriptase uses the pre-genomic RNA as a template for the creation of genomic DNA.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] whilst families *Belpaoviridae*, *Metaviridae*, *Pseudoviridae*, *Retroviridae*, and *Caulimoviridae* constitute the order *Ortervirales*.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Antiretroviral drugs are medications for the treatment of infection by retroviruses, primarily HIV.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Different classes of antiretroviral drugs act on different stages of the HIV life cycle.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Combination of several (typically three or four) antiretroviral drugs is known as highly active antiretroviral therapy (HAART).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/retrovirus] Feline leukemia virus and Feline immunodeficiency virus infections are treated with biologics, including the only immunomodulator currently licensed for sale in the United States, Lymphocyte T-Cell Immune Modulator (LTCI).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] Transduction was discovered in *Salmonella* by Norton Zinder and Joshua Lederberg at the University of Wisconsin–Madison in 1952.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] Transduction happens through either the lytic cycle or the lysogenic cycle.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] When bacteriophages (viruses that infect bacteria) that are lytic infect bacterial cells, they harness the replicational, transcriptional, and translation machinery of the host bacterial cell to make new viral particles (virions).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] The new phage particles are then released by lysis of the host.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] In the lysogenic cycle, the phage chromosome is integrated as a prophage into the bacterial chromosome, where it can stay dormant for extended periods of time.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] If the prophage is induced (by UV light for example), the phage genome is excised from the bacterial chromosome and initiates the lytic cycle, which culminates in lysis of the cell and the release of phage particles.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] Generalized transduction (see below) occurs in both cycles during the lytic stage, while specialized transduction (see below) occurs when a prophage is excised in the lysogenic cycle.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] The packaging of bacteriophage DNA into phage capsids has low fidelity.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] Small pieces of bacterial DNA may be packaged into the bacteriophage particles.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] There are two ways that this can lead to transduction.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] Generalized transduction occurs when random pieces of bacterial DNA are packaged into a phage.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] It happens when a phage is in the lytic stage, at the moment that the viral DNA is packaged into phage heads.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] If the virus replicates using 'headful packaging', it attempts to fill the head with genetic material.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] If the viral genome results in spare capacity, viral packaging mechanisms may incorporate bacterial genetic material into the new virion.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] Alternatively, generalized transduction may occur via recombination.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] Generalized transduction is a rare event and occurs on the order of 1 phage in 11,000.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] The new virus capsule that contains part bacterial DNA then infects another bacterial cell.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] If the DNA was originally a plasmid, it will re-circularize inside the new cell and become a plasmid again.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] If the new DNA matches with a homologous region of the recipient cell's chromosome, it will exchange DNA material similar to the actions in bacterial recombination.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] An example of specialized transduction is λ phage in *Escherichia coli*.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] Transduction with viral vectors can be used to insert or modify genes in mammalian cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] It is often used as a tool in basic research and is actively researched as a potential means for gene therapy.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] In these cases, a plasmid is constructed in which the genes to be transferred are flanked by viral sequences that are used by viral proteins to recognize and package the viral genome into viral particles.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] This plasmid is inserted (usually by transfection) into a producer cell together with other plasmids (DNA constructs) that carry the viral genes required for the formation of infectious virions.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] In these producer cells, the viral proteins expressed by these packaging constructs bind the sequences on the DNA/RNA (depending on the type of viral vector) to be transferred and insert it into viral particles.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] For safety, none of the plasmids used contains all the sequences required for virus formation, so that simultaneous transfection of multiple plasmids is required to get infectious virions.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] Moreover, only the plasmid carrying the sequences to be transferred contains signals that allow the genetic materials to be packaged in virions so that none of the genes encoding viral proteins are packaged.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] Viruses collected from these cells are then applied to the cells to be altered.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] The initial stages of these infections mimic infection with natural viruses and lead to expression of the genes transferred and (in the case of lentivirus/retrovirus vectors) insertion of the DNA to be transferred into the cellular genome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] However, since the transferred genetic material does not encode any of the viral genes, these infections do not generate new viruses (the viruses are "replication-deficient").
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transduction-genetics] Some enhancers have been used to improve transduction efficiency such as polybrene, protamine sulfate, retronectin, and DEAE Dextran.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] A **transgene** is a gene that has been transferred naturally, or by any of a number of genetic engineering techniques, from one organism to another.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The introduction of a transgene, in a process known as transgenesis, has the potential to change the phenotype of an organism.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] *Transgene* describes a segment of DNA containing a gene sequence that has been isolated from one organism and is introduced into a different organism.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] This non-native segment of DNA may either retain the ability to produce RNA or protein in the transgenic organism or alter the normal function of the transgenic organism's genetic code.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] In general, the DNA is incorporated into the organism's germ line.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] For example, in higher vertebrates this can be accomplished by injecting the foreign DNA into the nucleus of a fertilized ovum.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] This technique is routinely used to introduce human disease genes or other genes of interest into strains of laboratory mice to study the function or pathology involved with that particular gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The construction of a transgene requires the assembly of a few main parts.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The transgene must contain a promoter, which is a regulatory sequence that will determine where and when the transgene is active, an exon, a protein coding sequence (usually derived from the cDNA for the protein of interest), and a stop sequence.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] These are typically combined in a bacterial plasmid and the coding sequences are typically chosen from transgenes with previously known functions.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgenic or genetically modified organisms, be they bacteria, viruses or fungi, serve many research purposes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgenic plants, insects, fish and mammals (including humans) have been bred.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgenic plants such as corn and soybean have replaced wild strains in agriculture in some countries (e.g. the United States).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgene escape has been documented for GMO crops since 2001 with persistence and invasiveness.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgenetic organisms pose ethical questions and may cause biosafety problems.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The idea of shaping an organism to fit a specific need is not a new science.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] However, until the late 1900s farmers and scientists could breed new strains of a plant or organism only from closely related species because the DNA had to be compatible for offspring to be able to reproduce.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] In the 1970 and 1980s, scientists passed this hurdle by inventing procedures for combining the DNA of two vastly different species with genetic engineering.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The organisms produced by these procedures were termed transgenic.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgenesis is the same as gene therapy in the sense that they both transform cells for a specific purpose.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] However, they are completely different in their purposes, as gene therapy aims to cure a defect in cells, and transgenesis seeks to produce a genetically modified organism by incorporating the specific transgene into every cell and changing the genome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgenesis will therefore change the germ cells, not only the somatic cells, in order to ensure that the transgenes are passed down to the offspring when the organisms reproduce.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgenes alter the genome by blocking the function of a host gene; they can either replace the host gene with one that codes for a different protein, or introduce an additional gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The first transgenic organism was created in 1974 when Annie Chang and Stanley Cohen expressed *Staphylococcus aureus* genes in *Escherichia coli*.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] In 1978, yeast cells were the first eukaryotic organisms to undergo gene transfer.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Mouse cells were first transformed in 1979, followed by mouse embryos in 1980.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Most of the very first transmutations were performed by microinjection of DNA directly into cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The first transgenic animals were only intended for genetic research to study the specific function of a gene, and by 2003, thousands of genes had been studied.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] A variety of transgenic plants have been designed for agriculture to produce genetically modified crops, such as corn, soybean, rapeseed oil, cotton, rice and more.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] As of 2012, these GMO crops were planted on 170 million hectares globally.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] One example of a transgenic plant species is golden rice.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] In the late 20th century, an estimated five million children developed xerophthalmia, a medical condition caused by vitamin A deficiency, in Southeast Asia each year.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Of those children, a quarter million went blind.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] To combat this, scientists used biolistics to insert the daffodil phytoene synthase gene into indigenous rice cultivars.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The daffodil insertion increased the production of β-carotene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The product was a transgenic rice species rich in vitamin A, called golden rice.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Little is known about the impact of golden rice on xerophthalmia because anti-GMO campaigns have prevented the full commercial release of golden rice into agricultural systems in need.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The escape of genetically-engineered plant genes via hybridization with wild relatives was first discussed and examined in Mexico and Europe in the mid-1990s.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] There is agreement that escape of transgenes is inevitable, even "some proof that it is happening".
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Up until 2008 there were few documented cases.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Corn sampled in 2000 from the Sierra Juarez, Oaxaca, Mexico contained a transgenic 35S promoter, while a large sample taken by a different method from the same region in 2003 and 2004 did not.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] A sample from another region from 2002 also did not, but directed samples taken in 2004 did, suggesting transgene persistence or re-introduction.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] A 2009 study found recombinant proteins in 3.1% and 1.8% of samples, most commonly in southeast Mexico.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Seed and grain import from the United States could explain the frequency and distribution of transgenes in west-central Mexico, but not in the southeast.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Also, 5.0% of corn seed lots in Mexican corn stocks expressed recombinant proteins despite the moratorium on GM crops.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] In 2011, transgenic cotton was found in Mexico among wild cotton, after 15 years of GMO cotton cultivation.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgenic rapeseed *Brassicus napus* – hybridized with a native Japanese species, *Brassica rapa* – was found in Japan in 2011 after having been rectified with in 2006 in Québec, Canada.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] They were persistent over a six-year study period, without herbicide selection pressure and despite hybridization with the wild form.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] This was the first report of the introgression—the stable incorporation of genes from one gene pool into another—of an herbicide transgene from *Brassica napus* into the wild form gene pool.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgenic creeping bentgrass, engineered to be glyphosate-tolerant as "one of the first wind-pollinated, perennial, and highly outcrossing transgenic crops", was planted in 2003 as part of a large (about 160 ha) field trial in central Oregon near Madras, Oregon.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] In 2004, its pollen was found to have reached wild growing bentgrass populations up to 14 kilometres away.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Cross-pollinating *Agrostis gigantea* was even found at a distance of 21 kilometres.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The grower, Scotts Company could not remove all genetically engineered plants, and in 2007, the U.S.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Department of Agriculture fined Scotts $500,000 for noncompliance with regulations.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The long-term monitoring and controlling of a particular transgene has been shown not to be feasible.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The European Food Safety Authority published a guidance for risk assessment in 2010.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Genetically modified mice are the most common animal model for transgenic research.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgenic mouse are currently being used to study a variety of diseases including cancer, obesity, heart disease, arthritis, anxiety, and Parkinson's disease.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The two most common types of genetically modified mice are knockout mice and oncomice.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Knockout mice are a type of mouse model that uses transgenic insertion to disrupt an existing gene's expression.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] In order to create knockout mice, a transgene with the desired sequence is inserted into an isolated mouse blastocyst using electroporation.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Then, homologous recombination occurs naturally within some cells, replacing the gene of interest with the designed transgene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Through this process, researchers were able to demonstrate that a transgene can be integrated into the genome of an animal, serve a specific function within the cell, and be passed down to future generations.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Oncomice are another genetically modified mouse species created by inserting transgenes that increase the animal's vulnerability to cancer.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Cancer researchers utilize oncomice to study the profiles of different cancers in order to apply this knowledge to human studies.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Multiple studies have been conducted concerning transgenesis in *Drosophila melanogaster*, the fruit fly.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] This organism has been a helpful genetic model for over 100 years, due to its well-understood developmental pattern.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The transfer of transgenes into the *Drosophila* genome has been performed using various techniques, including P element, Cre-loxP, and ΦC31 insertion.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The most practiced method used thus far to insert transgenes into the *Drosophila* genome utilizes P elements.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The transposable P elements, also known as transposons, are segments of bacterial DNA that are translocated into the genome, without the presence of a complementary sequence in the host's genome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] P elements are administered in pairs of two, which flank the DNA insertion region of interest.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Additionally, P elements often consist of two plasmid components, one known as the P element transposase and the other, the P transposon backbone.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The transposase plasmid portion drives the transposition of the P transposon backbone, containing the transgene of interest and often a marker, between the two terminal sites of the transposon.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Success of this insertion results in the nonreversible addition of the transgene of interest into the genome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] While this method has been proven effective, the insertion sites of the P elements are often uncontrollable, resulting in an unfavorable, random insertion of the transgene into the *Drosophila* genome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] To improve the location and precision of the transgenic process, an enzyme known as Cre has been introduced.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Cre has proven to be a key element in a process known as recombinase-mediated cassette exchange (RMCE).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] While it has shown to have a lower efficiency of transgenic transformation than the P element transposases, Cre greatly lessens the labor-intensive abundance of balancing random P insertions.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Cre aids in the targeted transgenesis of the DNA gene segment of interest, as it supports the mapping of the transgene insertion sites, known as loxP sites.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] These sites, unlike P elements, can be specifically inserted to flank a chromosomal segment of interest, aiding in targeted transgenesis.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The Cre transposase is important in the catalytic cleavage of the base pairs present at the carefully positioned loxP sites, permitting more specific insertions of the transgenic donor plasmid of interest.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] To overcome the limitations and low yields that transposon-mediated and Cre-loxP transformation methods produce, the bacteriophage ΦC31 has recently been utilized.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Recent breakthrough studies involve the microinjection of the bacteriophage ΦC31 integrase, which shows improved transgene insertion of large DNA fragments that are unable to be transposed by P elements alone.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] This method involves the recombination between an attachment (attP) site in the phage and an attachment site in the bacterial host genome (attB).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Compared to usual P element transgene insertion methods, ΦC31 integrates the entire transgene vector, including bacterial sequences and antibiotic resistance genes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Unfortunately, the presence of these additional insertions has been found to affect the level and reproducibility of transgene expression.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] One agricultural application is to selectively breed animals for particular traits: Transgenic cattle with an increased muscle phenotype has been produced by overexpressing a short hairpin RNA with homology to the myostatin mRNA using RNA interference.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgenes are being used to produce milk with high levels of proteins or silk from the milk of goats.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Another agricultural application is to selectively breed animals, which are resistant to diseases or animals for biopharmaceutical production.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The application of transgenes is a rapidly growing area of molecular biology.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] As of 2005 it was predicted that in the next two decades, 300,000 lines of transgenic mice will be generated.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Researchers have identified many applications for transgenes, particularly in the medical field.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] As of 2004 there were five thousand known genetic diseases, and the potential to treat these diseases using transgenic animals is, perhaps, one of the most promising applications of transgenes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] There is a potential to use human gene therapy to replace a mutated gene with an unmutated copy of a transgene in order to treat the genetic disorder.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] This can be done through the use of Cre-Lox or knockout.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Moreover, genetic disorders are being studied through the use of transgenic mice, pigs, rabbits, and rats.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgenic rabbits have been created to study inherited cardiac arrhythmias, as the rabbit heart markedly better resembles the human heart as compared to the mouse.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] More recently, scientists have also begun using transgenic goats to study genetic disorders related to fertility.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgenes may be used for xenotransplantation from pig organs.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Through the study of xeno-organ rejection, it was found that an acute rejection of the transplanted organ occurs upon the organ's contact with blood from the recipient due to the recognition of foreign antibodies on endothelial cells of the transplanted organ.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Scientists have identified the antigen in pigs that causes this reaction, and therefore are able to transplant the organ without immediate rejection by removal of the antigen.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] However, the antigen begins to be expressed later on, and rejection occurs.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Therefore, further research is being conducted.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgenic microorganisms capable of producing catalytic proteins or enzymes which increase the rate of industrial reactions.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transgene use in humans is currently fraught with issues.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] Transformation of genes into human cells has not been perfected yet.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] The most famous example of this involved certain patients developing T-cell leukemia after being treated for X-linked severe combined immunodeficiency (X-SCID).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/transgene] This was attributed to the close proximity of the inserted gene to the LMO2 promoter, which controls the transcription of the LMO2 proto-oncogene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Gene therapy utilizes the delivery of DNA into cells, which can be accomplished by several methods, summarized below.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The two major classes of methods are those that use recombinant viruses (sometimes called biological nanoparticles or viral vectors) and those that use naked DNA or DNA complexes (non-viral methods).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] All viruses bind to their hosts and introduce their genetic material into the host cell as part of their replication cycle.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] This genetic material contains basic 'instructions' of how to produce more copies of these viruses, hacking the body's normal production machinery to serve the needs of the virus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The host cell will carry out these instructions and produce additional copies of the virus, leading to more and more cells becoming infected.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Some types of viruses insert their genome into the host's cytoplasm, but do not actually enter the cell.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Others penetrate the cell membrane disguised as protein molecules and enter the cell.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] There are two main types of virus infection: lytic and lysogenic.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Shortly after inserting its DNA, viruses of the lytic cycle quickly produce more viruses, burst from the cell and infect more cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Lysogenic viruses integrate their DNA into the DNA of the host cell and may live in the body for many years before responding to a trigger.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The virus reproduces as the cell does and does not inflict bodily harm until it is triggered.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The trigger releases the DNA from that of the host and employs it to create new viruses.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The genetic material in retroviruses is in the form of RNA molecules, while the genetic material of their hosts is in the form of DNA.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] When a retrovirus infects a host cell, it will introduce its RNA together with some enzymes, namely reverse transcriptase and integrase, into the cell.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] This RNA molecule from the retrovirus must produce a DNA copy from its RNA molecule before it can be integrated into the genetic material of the host cell.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The process of producing a DNA copy from an RNA molecule is termed reverse transcription.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] It is carried out by one of the enzymes carried in the virus, called reverse transcriptase.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] After this DNA copy is produced and is free in the nucleus of the host cell, it must be incorporated into the genome of the host cell.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] That is, it must be inserted into the large DNA molecules in the cell (the chromosomes).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] This process is done by another enzyme carried in the virus called integrase.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Now that the genetic material of the virus has been inserted, it can be said that the host cell has been modified to contain new genes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] If this host cell divides later, its descendants will all contain the new genes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Sometimes the genes of the retrovirus do not express their information immediately.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] One of the problems of gene therapy using retroviruses is that the integrase enzyme can insert the genetic material of the virus into any arbitrary position in the genome of the host; it randomly inserts the genetic material into a chromosome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] If genetic material happens to be inserted in the middle of one of the original genes of the host cell, this gene will be disrupted (insertional mutagenesis).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] If the gene happens to be one regulating cell division, uncontrolled cell division (i.e., cancer) can occur.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] This problem has recently begun to be addressed by utilizing zinc finger nucleases or by including certain sequences such as the beta-globin locus control region to direct the site of integration to specific chromosomal sites.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Gene therapy trials using retroviral vectors to treat X-linked severe combined immunodeficiency (X-SCID) represent the most successful application of gene therapy to date.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] More than twenty patients have been treated in France and Britain, with a high rate of immune system reconstitution observed.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Similar trials were restricted or halted in the US when leukemia was reported in patients treated in the French X-SCID gene therapy trial.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] To date, four children in the French trial and one in the British trial have developed leukemia as a result of insertional mutagenesis by the retroviral vector.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] All but one of these children responded well to conventional anti-leukemia treatment.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Gene therapy trials to treat SCID due to deficiency of the Adenosine Deaminase (ADA) enzyme (one form of SCID) continue with relative success in the US, Britain, Ireland, Italy and Japan.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Adenoviruses are viruses that carry their genetic material in the form of double-stranded DNA.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] They cause respiratory, intestinal, and eye infections in humans (especially the common cold).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] When these viruses infect a host cell, they introduce their DNA molecule into the host.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The genetic material of the adenoviruses is not incorporated (transient) into the host cell's genetic material.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The DNA molecule is left free in the nucleus of the host cell, and the instructions in this extra DNA molecule are transcribed just like any other gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The only difference is that these extra genes are not replicated when the cell is about to undergo cell division so the descendants of that cell will not have the extra gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] As a result, treatment with the adenovirus will require re-administration in a growing cell population although the absence of integration into the host cell's genome should prevent the type of cancer seen in the SCID trials.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] This vector system has been promoted for treating cancer and indeed the first gene therapy product to be licensed to treat cancer, Gendicine, is an adenovirus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Gendicine, an adenoviral p53-based gene therapy was approved by the Chinese food and drug regulators in 2003 for treatment of head and neck cancer.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Advexin, a similar gene therapy approach from Introgen, was turned down by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) in 2008.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Concerns about the safety of adenovirus vectors were raised after the 1999 death of Jesse Gelsinger while participating in a gene therapy trial.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Since then, work using adenovirus vectors has focused on genetically limited versions of the virus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Cytomegalovirus (CMV) is part of the β-herpesvirus subfamily that includes roseoloviruses.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] CMV coevolved with an assortment of mammalian hosts, including human CMV (HCMV), murine CMV (MCMV) and rhesus CMV (RhCMV).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] CMVs are characterized by large DNA genomes and typically asymptomatic infection in healthy hosts.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The first investigation into cytomegalovirus (CMV) as a gene therapy vector was published in 2000.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] CMV's tropism for hematopoietic progenitor cells and its large genome (230 kbp) initially attracted researchers.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] CMV-based vaccine vectors have since been used to induce T Cell response.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] More recently, CMV containing telomerase and follistatin was intravenously and intranasally delivered in mouse studies with the intention of extending healthspan.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The viral vectors described above have natural host cell populations that they infect most efficiently.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Retroviruses have limited natural host cell ranges, and although adenovirus and adeno-associated virus are able to infect a relatively broader range of cells efficiently, some cell types are resistant to infection by these viruses as well.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Attachment to and entry into a susceptible cell is mediated by the protein envelope on the surface of a virus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Retroviruses and adeno-associated viruses have a single protein coating their membrane, while adenoviruses are coated with both an envelope protein and fibers that extend away from the surface of the virus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] In either case, entry into potential host cells requires a favorable interaction between a protein on the surface of the virus and a protein on the surface of the cell.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] For the purposes of gene therapy, one might either want to limit or expand the range of cells susceptible to transduction by a gene therapy vector.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] To this end, many vectors have been developed in which the endogenous viral envelope proteins have been replaced by either envelope proteins from other viruses, or by chimeric proteins.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Such chimera would consist of those parts of the viral protein necessary for incorporation into the virion as well as sequences meant to interact with specific host cell proteins.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Viruses in which the envelope proteins have been replaced as described are referred to as pseudotyped viruses.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] For example, the most popular retroviral vector for use in gene therapy trials has been the lentivirus Simian immunodeficiency virus coated with the envelope proteins, G-protein, from Vesicular stomatitis virus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] This vector is referred to as VSV G-pseudotyped lentivirus, and infects an almost universal set of cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] This tropism is characteristic of the VSV G-protein with which this vector is coated.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Many attempts have been made to limit the tropism of viral vectors to one or a few host cell populations.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] This advance would allow for the systemic administration of a relatively small amount of vector.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The potential for off-target cell modification would be limited, and many concerns from the medical community would be alleviated.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Most attempts to limit tropism have used chimeric envelope proteins bearing antibody fragments.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] These vectors show great promise for the development of "magic bullet" gene therapies.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] A replication-competent vector called ONYX-015 is used in replicating tumor cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] It was found that in the absence of the E1B-55Kd viral protein, adenovirus caused very rapid apoptosis of infected, p53(+) cells, and this results in dramatically reduced virus progeny and no subsequent spread.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Apoptosis was mainly the result of the ability of EIA to inactivate p300.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] In p53(-) cells, deletion of E1B 55kd has no consequence in terms of apoptosis, and viral replication is similar to that of wild-type virus, resulting in massive killing of cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] A replication-defective vector deletes some essential genes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] These deleted genes are still necessary in the body so they are replaced with either a helper virus or a DNA molecule.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Replication-defective vectors always contain a "transfer construct".
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The transfer construct carries the gene to be transduced or "transgene".
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The transfer construct also carries the sequences which are necessary for the general functioning of the viral genome: packaging sequence, repeats for replication and, when needed, priming of reverse transcription.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] These are denominated cis-acting elements, because they need to be on the same piece of DNA as the viral genome and the gene of interest.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Trans-acting elements are viral elements, which can be encoded on a different DNA molecule.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] For example, the viral structural proteins can be expressed from a different genetic element than the viral genome.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The herpes simplex virus is a human neurotropic virus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] This is mostly examined for gene transfer in the nervous system.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The wild type HSV-1 virus is able to infect neurons and evade the host immune response, but may still become reactivated and produce a lytic cycle of viral replication.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Therefore, it is typical to use mutant strains of HSV-1 that are deficient in their ability to replicate.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Though the latent virus is not transcriptionally apparent, it does possess neuron specific promoters that can continue to function normally.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Antibodies to HSV-1 are common in humans, however complications due to herpes infection are somewhat rare.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Caution for rare cases of encephalitis must be taken and this provides some rationale to using HSV-2 as a viral vector as it generally has tropism for neuronal cells innervating the urogenital area of the body and could then spare the host of severe pathology in the brain.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Non-viral methods present certain advantages over viral methods, with simple large scale production and low host immunogenicity being just two.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Previously, low levels of transfection and expression of the gene held non-viral methods at a disadvantage; however, recent advances in vector technology have yielded molecules and techniques with transfection efficiencies similar to those of viruses.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] This is the simplest method of non-viral transfection.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Clinical trials carried out of intramuscular injection of a naked DNA plasmid have occurred with some success; however, the expression has been very low in comparison to other methods of transfection.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] In addition to trials with plasmids, there have been trials with naked PCR product, which have had similar or greater success.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Cellular uptake of naked DNA is generally inefficient.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Research efforts focusing on improving the efficiency of naked DNA uptake have yielded several novel methods, such as electroporation, sonoporation, and the use of a "gene gun", which shoots DNA coated gold particles into the cell using high pressure gas.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Electroporation is a method that uses short pulses of high voltage to carry DNA across the cell membrane.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] This shock is thought to cause temporary formation of pores in the cell membrane, allowing DNA molecules to pass through.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Electroporation is generally efficient and works across a broad range of cell types.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] However, a high rate of cell death following electroporation has limited its use, including clinical applications.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] More recently a newer method of electroporation, termed electron-avalanche transfection, has been used in gene therapy experiments.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] By using a high-voltage plasma discharge, DNA was efficiently delivered following very short (microsecond) pulses.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Compared to electroporation, the technique resulted in greatly increased efficiency and less cellular damage.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The use of particle bombardment, or the gene gun, is another physical method of DNA transfection.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] In this technique, DNA is coated onto gold particles and loaded into a device which generates a force to achieve penetration of the DNA into the cells, leaving the gold behind on a "stopping" disk.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Sonoporation uses ultrasonic frequencies to deliver DNA into cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The process of acoustic cavitation is thought to disrupt the cell membrane and allow DNA to move into cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] In a method termed magnetofection, DNA is complexed to magnetic particles, and a magnet is placed underneath the tissue culture dish to bring DNA complexes into contact with a cell monolayer.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Hydrodynamic delivery involves rapid injection of a high volume of a solution into vasculature (such as into the inferior vena cava, bile duct, or tail vein).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The solution contains molecules that are to be inserted into cells, such as DNA plasmids or siRNA, and transfer of these molecules into cells is assisted by the elevated hydrostatic pressure caused by the high volume of injected solution.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The use of synthetic oligonucleotides in gene therapy is to deactivate the genes involved in the disease process.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] There are several methods by which this is achieved.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] One strategy uses antisense specific to the target gene to disrupt the transcription of the faulty gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Another uses small molecules of RNA called siRNA to signal the cell to cleave specific unique sequences in the mRNA transcript of the faulty gene, disrupting translation of the faulty mRNA, and therefore expression of the gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] A further strategy uses double stranded oligodeoxynucleotides as a decoy for the transcription factors that are required to activate the transcription of the target gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The transcription factors bind to the decoys instead of the promoter of the faulty gene, which reduces the transcription of the target gene, lowering expression.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Additionally, single stranded DNA oligonucleotides have been used to direct a single base change within a mutant gene.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The oligonucleotide is designed to anneal with complementarity to the target gene with the exception of a central base, the target base, which serves as the template base for repair.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] This technique is referred to as oligonucleotide mediated gene repair, targeted gene repair, or targeted nucleotide alteration.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] To improve the delivery of the new DNA into the cell, the DNA must be protected from damage and positively charged.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Initially, anionic and neutral lipids were used for the construction of lipoplexes for synthetic vectors.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] However, in spite of the facts that there is little toxicity associated with them, that they are compatible with body fluids and that there was a possibility of adapting them to be tissue specific; they are complicated and time-consuming to produce so attention was turned to the cationic versions.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Cationic lipids, due to their positive charge, were first used to condense negatively charged DNA molecules so as to facilitate the encapsulation of DNA into liposomes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Later it was found that the use of cationic lipids significantly enhanced the stability of lipoplexes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Also as a result of their charge, cationic liposomes interact with the cell membrane, endocytosis was widely believed as the major route by which cells uptake lipoplexes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Endosomes are formed as the results of endocytosis, however, if genes can not be released into cytoplasm by breaking the membrane of endosome, they will be sent to lysosomes where all DNA will be destroyed before they could achieve their functions.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] It was also found that although cationic lipids themselves could condense and encapsulate DNA into liposomes, the transfection efficiency is very low due to the lack of ability in terms of "endosomal escaping".
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] However, when helper lipids (usually electroneutral lipids, such as DOPE) were added to form lipoplexes, much higher transfection efficiency was observed.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Later on, it was discovered that certain lipids have the ability to destabilize endosomal membranes so as to facilitate the escape of DNA from endosome, therefore those lipids are called fusogenic lipids.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Although cationic liposomes have been widely used as an alternative for gene delivery vectors, a dose dependent toxicity of cationic lipids were also observed which could limit their therapeutic usages.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The most common use of lipoplexes has been in gene transfer into cancer cells, where the supplied genes have activated tumor suppressor control genes in the cell and decrease the activity of oncogenes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Recent studies have shown lipoplexes to be useful in transfecting respiratory epithelial cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Polymersomes are synthetic versions of liposomes (vesicles with a lipid bilayer), made of amphiphilic block copolymers.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] They can encapsulate either hydrophilic or hydrophobic contents and can be used to deliver cargo such as DNA, proteins, or drugs to cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Advantages of polymersomes over liposomes include greater stability, mechanical strength, blood circulation time, and storage capacity.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Complexes of polymers with DNA are called polyplexes.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Most polyplexes consist of cationic polymers and their fabrication is based on self-assembly by ionic interactions.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] One important difference between the methods of action of polyplexes and lipoplexes is that polyplexes cannot directly release their DNA load into the cytoplasm.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] As a result, co-transfection with endosome-lytic agents such as inactivated adenovirus was required to facilitate nanoparticle escape from the endocytic vesicle made during particle uptake.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] However, a better understanding of the mechanisms by which DNA can escape from endolysosomal pathway, i.e. proton sponge effect, has triggered new polymer synthesis strategies such as incorporation of protonable residues in polymer backbone and has revitalized research on polycation-based systems.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Due to their low toxicity, high loading capacity, and ease of fabrication, polycationic nanocarriers demonstrate great promise compared to their rivals such as viral vectors which show high immunogenicity and potential carcinogenicity, and lipid-based vectors which cause dose dependence toxicity.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Polyethyleneimine and chitosan are among the polymeric carriers that have been extensively studied for development of gene delivery therapeutics.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Other polycationic carriers such as poly(beta-amino esters) and polyphosphoramidate are being added to the library of potential gene carriers.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] In addition to the variety of polymers and copolymers, the ease of controlling the size, shape, surface chemistry of these polymeric nano-carriers gives them an edge in targeting capability and taking advantage of enhanced permeability and retention effect.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] A dendrimer is a highly branched macromolecule with a spherical shape.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The surface of the particle may be functionalized in many ways and many of the properties of the resulting construct are determined by its surface.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] In particular it is possible to construct a cationic dendrimer, i.e. one with a positive surface charge.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] When in the presence of genetic material such as DNA or RNA, charge complementarity leads to a temporary association of the nucleic acid with the cationic dendrimer.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] On reaching its destination the dendrimer-nucleic acid complex is then taken into the cell via endocytosis.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] In recent years the benchmark for transfection agents has been cationic lipids.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Limitations of these competing reagents have been reported to include: the lack of ability to transfect some cell types, the lack of robust active targeting capabilities, incompatibility with animal models, and toxicity.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Dendrimers offer robust covalent construction and extreme control over molecule structure, and therefore size.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Together these give compelling advantages compared to existing approaches.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Producing dendrimers has historically been a slow and expensive process consisting of numerous slow reactions, an obstacle that severely curtailed their commercial development.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] The Michigan-based company Dendritic Nanotechnologies discovered a method to produce dendrimers using kinetically driven chemistry, a process that not only reduced cost by a magnitude of three, but also cut reaction time from over a month to several days.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] These new "Priostar" dendrimers can be specifically constructed to carry a DNA or RNA payload that transfects cells at a high efficiency with little or no toxicity.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Inorganic nanoparticles, such as gold, silica, iron oxide (ex. magnetofection) and calcium phosphates have been shown to be capable of gene delivery.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Some of the benefits of inorganic vectors is in their storage stability, low manufacturing cost and often time, low immunogenicity, and resistance to microbial attack.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Nanosized materials less than 100 nm have been shown to efficiently trap the DNA or RNA and allows its escape from the endosome without degradation.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Inorganics have also been shown to exhibit improved in vitro transfection for attached cell lines due to their increased density and preferential location on the base of the culture dish.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Quantum dots have also been used successfully and permits the coupling of gene therapy with a stable fluorescence marker.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Engineered organic nanoparticles are also under development, which could be used for co-delivery of genes and therapeutic agents.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Cell-penetrating peptides (CPPs), also known as peptide transduction domains (PTDs), are short peptides (< 40 amino acids) that efficiently pass through cell membranes while being covalently or non-covalently bound to various molecules, thus facilitating these molecules' entry into cells.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Cell entry occurs primarily by endocytosis but other entry mechanisms also exist.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Examples of cargo molecules of CPPs include nucleic acids, liposomes, and drugs of low molecular weight.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] CPP cargo can be directed into specific cell organelles by incorporating localization sequences into CPP sequences.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] For example, nuclear localization sequences are commonly used to guide CPP cargo into the nucleus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] For guidance into mitochondria, a mitochondrial targeting sequence can be used; this method is used in protofection (a technique that allows for foreign mitochondrial DNA to be inserted into cells' mitochondria).
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Due to every method of gene transfer having shortcomings, there have been some hybrid methods developed that combine two or more techniques.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Virosomes are one example; they combine liposomes with an inactivated HIV or influenza virus.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] This has been shown to have more efficient gene transfer in respiratory epithelial cells than either viral or liposomal methods alone.
[src:gene-therapy-vectors/vectors-in-gene-therapy] Other methods involve mixing other viral vectors with cationic lipids or hybridising viruses.
